Finished building a React Native for freshpaint.io. It's a babel plugin that modifies your React Native app and instruments every part of your app automatically. This allows you to get analytics for different features in your app without writing any code beside the initial SDK installation.

Hey guys! Been working on a note taking app since the past 20ish days. 
I have embedded features based on the use cases of modern day knowledge management.

1. Save links to articles, tweets, vids you find while browsing. 
2. Quick note taking, no titles, no modals, one click.
3. Connect your quick notes and links to pages to better sync and generate insights.
4. Gamified environment! Keyboard shortcuts to almost throw your mouse away!! It saves everything instantly, no button to forget to press.
5. Make your notes public without leaving the workspace and they will reflect on a minimalistic personal blog provided.

The development is half done, I am seeking UI designer to manage the placement of all the features.
I got 270+ beta signups overnight. I tweeted yesternight and it just blew up.

Here's the landing page - https://kotaru.vercel.app/

I'm working on an app to assist people in learning french
the app is going to work similarly to duolingo. I'm going to use the sentence parses to figure out what words they get wrong as they attempt to translate the sentences
oh
wait you might have just been asking what "pour" means
it means "for"
r u french
yes but I can’t speak the language very well
grew up in the us
could you explain me more what you´re doing? I'm really interested in tech for language learning
basically my goal is to facilitate intensive reading
I have a few french books that've collected and from them I extract all their words and sentences
then my goal is to have the app use spaced repetition to train you until you can read 98% of the words in the easiest book
(once you can read 98% of the words in a text, you can comfortably pick up the rest of the words from context)
the idea is that once you can read simple books it's more enjoyable to pick up vocabulary through reading than through flashcards
Yea I 100% agree that reading is useful, I've found that I learn more words when I see them again after having seen the definition prior

But what about the case of understanding grammar? What I mean is, for example if you're reading a French book and you see the word "pour". In many cases this would be = to "for" in english, but not in all cases. Or are you just looking at vocab?
that's sort of what the sentence thing I showed above was for
I don't think the french grammar is really that hard for english speakers tbh
so I'm not that worried about it
my app I think will mostly work by asking you to translate sentences
so hopefully you'll be able to pick up enough grammar from that to start reading
Ah I see, but I would say that to some degree some conceptual translating would be needed. As in, translating chunks of vocab and not the individual words
Like similar to the fact that there aren't any phrasal verbs in romance language, but there is in English.
Yes I agree
that's actually exactly what the screenshot I showed above is for haha
so for instance say the app shows you the sentence "j'ai mangé" which translates to "I ate"
I think how it will work is first "j" will be highlighted and you'll be expected to type "I", then "ai mangé" will be highlighted and you'll be expected to type "ate"
this requires sort of having the sentence split into chunks of associated words in both translations, so creating those is what the tool I'm developing in that screenshot is for

Oh lmao my bad didn't see you posted something related to this, then that's pretty cool you got that covered. I'm starting to use duo for French right now. I can definitely see how it goes in the direction of "direct-translation", when languages aren't meant to be like that.
I did the entire duolingo tree for french twice, and the second time I reviewed all the old lessons every day as I was going it so they were all gold the entire time
and I still don't know shit about french

My view on Duolingo is that it only helps in the beginning, and only for the latin alphabet languages. After you have like a basic understanding of verbs, vocab, etc... it's time to move on. I went through halfway of the spanish one, and stopped after seeing how repetitive it was.
I agree
honestly my opinion is that if you want to learn a language you need to stop being a pussy and just move to a country that speaks the language you want to learn
but it's obviously nice to have some language skill first
I don't agree there. A lot of people don't have that privilege, and I think the tech that most of the world has today enables them to learn a language even up to native level.
And that tech is even improving
Sure, you will have more opportunity for immersion if you move to the country, but immersion is still definitely possible with tech today
You can learn a language without being there, but it's so much more effort

it's sad that not everyone has the ability (actually I'd expect even most decently well off americans don't, you'd need to leave your job and go find temporary employment in a foreign country which is very difficult)
seeing the difference between me, who's taken 4 years of french and done duolingo twice, and my sister who spent like 10 months in france, was striking
there was no comparison in our language ability, she was way ahead of me

Yea of course, but we also have to admit the effort that it takes when you go to the country. There's also people in go and get nothing. I think the difference in the case of your sister and you wasn't just the difference in going to a country, but the way it was learned
I took spanish for 8-9 years, and when I left HS the only thing I knew was "Hello how are you, I have 3 dogs"
But not until a few years later, utilizing duolingo, intense vocab, immersion, and much more, did I reach a really high level after like 1.5 years
Ofc duolingo was just the first step though, I honestly stopped using it <2 months in.
But yes, if you do go to a foreign country definitely take advantage of it because you have a fantastic opportunity to learn a language
this is just so true
I think you can actually get pretty far with tech
in class you can't really do as much because it's hard to do SRS in class

Yea it's not efficient in schools. In schools they don't foster any interest in the language, and I felt like every year we just learned past tense over and over again. I think another thing is people need to learn how to learn a language,
do you have any advice on learning how to learn?

Well for one to figure out how to learn how to learn, I think it's all about personal researching and figuring out what works for you. Even looking at some of the internet polyglots, sometimes they have some very good advice even if some of them are a bit fake lmao.

For some actual advice to learning a language, from what I've learned so far. I definitely think people need to stop using a lot of duolingo (even if I think it can be a good tool). Vocabulary is probably the most important, and used in conjunction with any form of reading (this doesn't have to be a book). Immersion is super useful, but I've found that just randomly throwing on a show without subtitles that you understand <20% isn't very useful besides maybe accustoming yourself to the language
I don't think speaking is as useful as people think, but it can help you memorize some words that you struggle with.

And it's all about gauging where your at. Again, immersion is important but it has to be immersion that you believe you can get something out of. So like maybe a book that you understand 60-70% of. And just trying many things

I think a lot of people get stuck on a lot of courses (some that are paid), don't try anything else and then end there. But there's so many ways to improve and get even beyond fluent it's actually amazing.
Man that was a rant lmao

I think watching tv shows with captions on helps depending on the language. You can turn captions on and off after “learning benchmarks” to really test yourself. Could be as simple as that country / language reality tv and or soap opera so that you have context within learning.

Yea captions can really help tbh. I also include that as a form of reading. Before you can understand the a show without subtitles/captions, you would obviously have to understand it with it. So it's really just taking steps.

I would almost argue with remote culture and events / programming to listen in on live webinars / virtual events. There is the chat box open to read from and learning about a subject live could also be of help for basic comprehension and some fluency.
Yea definitely, theres so many different ways. And it's good to try it with many different videos/events/shows because different topics will speak differently and have diff vocab
I do this and it’s sooo helpful. I’ve also been told watching kids programs is the best because they use simpler vocab/grammar, although I’ve never tried that myself.
I'm going to try the kids show/books for my next language, but I know for a fact it can really help. As long as you're willing to be patient enough to watch kids shows lmao

Yeah that's why I haven't tried it yet. But I'm wondering - Is there a platform that helps you learn a language like this? Like a service that organizes and provides resources to learn languages through exposure to Tv/Movies/etc., instead of the traditional way of just memorizing vocab ad nauseam?

@Jeremy B @mnathl I literally watched Detective Conan / Case Closed for years in mandarin (it was dubbed) to learn it at least conversationally. Helped me a lot although I guess I picked up way too many murder / crime scene phrases and I’m not tryna be a prosecutor. 

I’d be more interested in dubbing / translating tech in general for voice to text/live captioning. Currently it’s very labor intensive and expensive to make dubbing happen for international media even though I’m a subtitles person myself. If dubbing was more accurate and less cringe lined up visually, various niche film media would be consumed by all markets in a different way. Like how many Americans really watch shows that aren’t American made and / or anime. Lolz.

I gotta believe that someone is working on a product that can accurately mass-translate/dub films to other languages. Not surprised it hasn't happened yet though because of how many awkwardly translated films are out there, like you said.

Also difficult because of context and cultural phrases and metaphors. If there was a simultaneous updating dubbing / captions that worked across platforms with a user submitted dictionary database similar to urban dictionary, could be interesting. 🤪🤪🤪

It would be amazing if that did exist. I think I did hear of an app that sorta did that for Mandarin. It didnt mass translate, but it guided you threw many different movies in Mandarin, and helped you pick up phrases
